# React Fundamentals

React is a **UI-as-a-function** library. The core idea: your entire UI is the output of calling a function with some data. Give it the same data, get the same screen. Change the data, React figures out the smallest set of DOM changes needed to match.

```
     Data (props + state)
          │
          ▼  Your component functions
     Virtual DOM   ← lightweight JS object tree
          │
          ▼  React's reconciler (the "diff")
     Minimal DOM patches
          │
          ▼
     Real browser DOM → pixels on screen
```

## JSX — HTML inside JavaScript

JSX is syntactic sugar. The browser never sees it — the build tool (Vite/Babel) transforms it to `React.createElement()` calls.

```tsx
// What you write
const el = <h1 className="title">Hello</h1>;

// What the compiler emits
const el = React.createElement('h1', { className: 'title' }, 'Hello');

// JSX rules:
// 1. One root element (or use <> Fragment shorthand)
// 2. Attributes use camelCase: className, onClick, htmlFor
// 3. Expressions in {curly braces}
// 4. Self-closing tags must close: <img />, <br />

const Greeting = ({ name }: { name: string }) => (
  <div>
    <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>        {/* expression */}
    <p>Today is {new Date().toDateString()}</p>
  </div>
);
```

## Components — the building blocks

A component is a **function that returns JSX** (or null). React calls it, gets a virtual DOM description, and paints accordingly.

```
     App
    /   \
  Nav   Page
        /  \
     List  Sidebar
     /  \
  Item  Item

Each box is a function call.
Each function returns a JSX description.
React assembles the whole tree and renders it.
```

```tsx
// Functional component — the modern standard
type CardProps = {
  title: string;
  body: string;
  onClick?: () => void;
};

function Card({ title, body, onClick }: CardProps) {
  return (
    <article onClick={onClick}>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{body}</p>
    </article>
  );
}

// Usage — props are just function arguments
<Card title="TypeScript" body="Static types" onClick={() => alert('clicked')} />
```

## Props — data flows down, events flow up

```
         <App data={users} />
              │  data down
              ▼
         <UserList users={users} onSelect={setSelected} />
              │  data down        event up ↑
              ▼
         <UserRow user={u} onClick={() => onSelect(u)} />
```

Props are **read-only**. A component must NEVER mutate its own props — this would break React's one-directional data flow guarantee.

```tsx
// ✗ WRONG — never mutate props
function Badge({ count }: { count: number }) {
  count++;  // TS error + logical bug
  return <span>{count}</span>;
}

// ✓ CORRECT — derive a new value
function Badge({ count }: { count: number }) {
  const display = count + 1;  // derived, not mutated
  return <span>{display}</span>;
}
```

## Virtual DOM — the diff engine

React never directly tells the browser 'change this div'. Instead:
1. Calls your component functions → builds a **virtual DOM** (plain JS objects)
2. Compares the new virtual DOM with the previous snapshot (the **diff**)
3. Converts only the *differences* into real DOM operations

```
Previous vDOM:         New vDOM after state change:
<ul>                   <ul>
  <li>Alice</li>         <li>Alice</li>
  <li>Bob</li>           <li>Bob</li>
</ul>                    <li>Charlie</li>  ← only this DOM node is added
                       </ul>

 React only calls createElement for <li>Charlie</li>
 → 1 DOM operation instead of rebuilding the whole list
```

## Keys — help React match old and new elements

When you render a list, React needs a way to match items in the old and new virtual DOM. **Keys are that identity signal.**

```tsx
// ✗ Using array index as key — breaks on reorder/insert
{items.map((item, i) => <li key={i}>{item.name}</li>)}

// ✓ Using stable unique id
{items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}

// Without keys / wrong keys:
// React may REUSE the wrong DOM node → stale input state, animation glitches
```

```
With key=id:   items=[A, B, C]  →  insert D at start  →  [D, A, B, C]
  React matches A↔A, B↔B, C↔C by key, only creates D  → 1 DOM op

With key=index: same operation
  React sees index 0 changed A→D, 1 changed B→A, 2 changed C→B, 3 is new C
  → 4 DOM ops + potential state bugs
```

## Conditional Rendering

```tsx
// Ternary — two branches
{isLoggedIn ? <Dashboard /> : <Login />}

// Short-circuit — one branch (falsy = render nothing)
{error && <ErrorBanner message={error} />}

// Careful: 0 is falsy but JSX renders it as '0' text!
// Use Boolean coercion:
{count > 0 && <Badge count={count} />}  // ✓
{!!count && <Badge count={count} />}    // ✓
{count && <Badge count={count} />}      // ✗ renders '0' when count=0
```

## Complexity Cheatsheet

| Concept | Key rule |
|---|---|
| Component re-render | Happens when props or state change |
| Props mutation | Never — always read-only |
| Key for lists | Must be stable, unique, not array index |
| JSX compilation | Transformed to createElement at build time |
| Fragment `<>` | Groups elements without adding a DOM node |

## Common Pitfalls
- Using array index as list `key` — causes state bugs on reorder
- `{count && <X />}` renders `0` when count is zero — use `count > 0 &&`
- Mutating props — breaks data flow, causes unreliable rendering
- Returning two sibling elements without a wrapper or Fragment
- Forgetting that JSX must use `className`, not `class`

## Connections
- **react-state-effects** — add state and side effects to components
- **react-rendering** — deep dive into reconciliation and when components re-render
- **ts-fundamentals** — type your props with TypeScript interfaces
- **react-hooks** — custom hooks extract and reuse stateful logic

